node.text:
Have you ever heard of crater feeding dolphins? Comment with a heart if you agree that this is the only type of drilling that should be taking place in The Bahamas. I jumped into the crystal-clear waters below as the SeaLegacy 1 came to a crawl, hoping to catch a glimpse of a recently-spotted pod of bottlenose dolphins. It was a long shot, given this particular species is notoriously skittish, but I decided it was still worth the try. I was not disappointed. I power-kicked to the sandy bottom at 60 feet deep and became mesmerized by behavior I had never seen before. The dolphins were using their echolocation to spot single, silver fish hiding deep in the soft sand. They would dive in with their snouts, sometimes all the way down to their pectoral fins, before wriggling back out with their catch. Imagine the incredible senses they have evolved through time! I could not believe they let me within a couple of feet with my noisy scuba bubbles as if I didn’t exist. As the Bahamas Petroleum Company (BPC) announces they did not find commercial quantities of oil at their test well (amazing news, but only a temporary setback for a company with many other areas leased nearby), it occurs to me that “crater feeding” by dolphins is the only type of drilling that should ever happen in these waters. The Bahamian blue tourism economy is worth far more to the people here than a risky experiment in resource extraction. The only appropriate thing for all governments to do if we want to achieve carbon balance is to permanently ban any further oil exploration – especially true for a nation that is still recovering from Dorian, one of the worst hurricanes in recorded history.
